Data_Description: County Business Patterns (CBP) is an annual series that provides subnational economic data for establishments with paid employees by industry and employment size. This series includes the number of establishments, employment during the week of March 12, first quarter payroll, and annual payroll.
Data_Provenance: Census produces the data using the Business Register
Coverage: 1964 - present; although data avilable from 1986- present, or 2012 - present (data.census.gov)
Geography: National, state, county, Metropolitan/Micropolitan Statistical Area (MSA), Combined Statistical Area (CSA), ZIP code, and Congressional District levels. Data for Puerto Rico and the Island Areas are available at the State and County Equivalent levels
Citation: U.S. Census Bureau. Economic Surveys, County Business Patterns, https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/cbp.html. Accessed on April 9, 2024.

Variable_Description: Percent of the total population who resides in a rural area
Interpretation: The percent of all persons in the nation, state and down to local area, that live in a non-urban area (i.e. areas where there are less than 2,500 residents)
Data_Description: The U.S. census counts each resident of the country, where they live on April 1, every ten years ending in zero. The Constitution mandates the enumeration to determine how to apportion the House of Representatives among the states.
Geography: Legal and statistical areas

Variable_Description: This is a modeled variable using information from a variety of sources which are determinants of food insecurity
Interpretation: The percent of all households in the nation, state and down to the county that struggles to afford food on a weekly basis
Data_Description: Map the Meal Gap features annual food insecurity estimates for the overall population and children in every county, congressional district, and state, as well as for every service area within our nationwide network of food banks
Geography: state, county

Variable_Label: Indicator of Low Access to Grocery Stores
Variable_Description: Indicator of whether a large share of the population in the Census tract has low access to a supermarket (i.e. the closest supermarket is more than one mile away in urban areas and more than 10 miles away in rural areas).
Interpretation: An indicator of whether a significant number of people in a Census tract have to travel more than one mile in urban areas or 10 miles in rural areas to get to a supermarket.
Data_Description: Presents an overview of food access indicators for low-income and other census tracts using different measures of supermarket accessibility
Metadata_link: (Some metadata is on a tab within the data); https://www.ers.usda.gov/data-products/food-access-research-atlas/documentation/
Geography: tract

Variable_Label: Percent of the Population who self-reported fair or poor health
Variable_Description: Statisitically modeled measure using survey data from the CDC’s Behavioral Risk Factor Surveillance System to estimate health measures and indicators for lower level geographies
Interpretation: The percent of all persons who are 18 years old and older in the state and down to the county, that reported they have fair or poor health
Source: PLACES: Local Data for Better Health
Metadata_link: (Some metadata avilable on each page for the download); https://www.cdc.gov/places/methodology/index.html
Geography: County, places, Census tract, ZCTA
